<dl id="n38216f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38216f">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38216f"> 216(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> karma <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n38216f"><li>FW 237.22 </li><li><a href="../../flex/kc/lexkc.htm#n38216f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/kc/l39kc.htm#n38216f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n38216f">MS BL 47477-69</ms> </li><li>JJA 51:088 <a name="kcd2y" href="../../FF/fdra/kda.htm#kcd2y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/kc/kcd2.htm#n38216f">Draft: II.1&sect;3.2</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">But we must not suppose that Hindus avoid pollution merely because of the trouble and expense which it causes. To the orthodox it really matters. It has for them &ldquo;the nature of sin&rdquo;. It affects their <mark>karma</mark>, and, therefore, their status in their next life. That high-cast lady would genuinely believe that she had been made unclean, that her ceremonial purity had been besmirched, by the propinquity of those unclean outcastes if they had dared tom come too near to her. Ceremonial purity is, indeed, for the reason just mentioned, the Hindu&apos;s most prized possession. <small> Rev W.S. Hunt, <a name="WSHI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WSHI"><cite title="source">India's Outcastes: A New Era</cite></a> (1924) 16</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Karma: A Hindu (and Buddhist) belief that holds that each possesses a sort of spiritual accounting, in which good and bad actions affect a person&apos;s standing in successive incarnations. A person&apos;s karma determines whether they are reincarnated in a higher or lower state of being, including determining cast standing in successive reincarnations.</mm> </dd></dl>
